english:
  title: Preface to the Spring and Autumn Annals of Wu and Yue
  author: Choe Hang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    His Majesty summoned me and spoke thus: "I have long held a love for historical study. The Spring and Autumn Annals of Wu and Yue, being of the historians' tradition, records the successes and failures of affairs in those times, serving as a mirror for posterity. Its value as historical evidence is considerable. Once I received the command of Emperor Wenzong to compile the Military Essentials of All Dynasties, and I included therein the actual deeds of Wu and Yue. Yet constrained by format and precedent, I could only extract what was essential to military matters, and thus the account remained incomplete. Regretting this incompleteness, I took as my foundation the work compiled by Zhao Ye of the Later Han, and cross-referenced it with the Zuo Commentary, the Discourses on the States, the Intrigues of the Warring States, Liu Xiang's Garden of Sayings, and other texts. I sought comprehensiveness: supplementing what was lacking, removing what was redundant, arranging the narrative thread, and correcting errors and falsehoods. Thus was one complete work achieved. Should it not be further collated and annotated?" At this, I and Shin Suk-ju undertook the task and, after several months of labor, presented the work. His Majesty bestowed upon it a name and commanded me to write this preface.

    I humbly reflect that the peace or peril, the rise or fall of kingdoms and states do not come of themselves. Rather, they depend entirely upon whether the ruler and his ministers act well or poorly. History exists to record such successes and failures, to transmit lessons of encouragement and warning. When one stands a thousand years hence and seeks to discourse upon affairs a thousand years past, without records to consult, even a sage could not foresee the truth or venture an opinion. Since the decline of antiquity, chaos has been frequent, and the guardianship of historical records has failed; documents have been scattered and lost. Only through the efforts of learned men and great talents, gathering widely and preserving comprehensively, can the blindness and deafness of later generations be remedied. Thus did the ancients, beyond the orthodox histories and chronological records, create separate compilations. Though their form may not be pure and their facts sometimes questionable, their words occasionally unpolished, they nonetheless gathered and preserved the events of their time with abundance rather than parsimony. This enabled later great collectors to draw upon them as resources. The Spring and Autumn Annals of Chu and Han are of this sort.

    Yet the affairs of Central China, being copiously recorded and widely transmitted, still cause scholars to lament occasional gaps. How much more so with Wu and Yue, isolated in the southeastern corner, having nothing in common with the lands of the north—their records scarce, their accounts sparse. That such works have been transmitted to the present day is surely a fortunate providence. Observe their territories and their endless warfare; the schemes and strategies of rulers and ministers; the maneuvers of attack and defense; the advancement and fall of the loyal and the treacherous; the strength and weakness of nations; the flourishing and decline of dynasties—all lie before the eye. There is much to encourage and much to warn against. How could such matters be neglected and left unexamined, omitted and uncorroborated?

    I reverently consider that our Majesty possesses a wisdom bestowed by Heaven, a brilliance renewed each day. Even before ascending the throne, he devoted himself to reading with constancy, mastering all schools of learning, penetrating the affairs of antiquity. Not a single obscure text or popular tale escaped his eye and deliberation. As for this work, he granted it his particular attention, examining it personally with meticulous care, untangling the most knotted complexities, revealing what was hidden, recovering what was lost, preserving both beginning and end, distinguishing true from false, making the editing luminous and the arrangement precise, so that all who study it find nothing lacking and all who verify find reliable evidence. Thus has the Spring and Autumn Annals of Wu and Yue finally become a work of true worth—something no mere ruler of old, hastily gathering and claiming credit for scholarship, could equal even in the slightest measure.

    Observe: Wu rose because it could employ heroic talents like Sun Wu; it fell because it would not heed the remonstrations of Wu Yuan. Yue's defeat came from ignoring the warnings of Fan Li; its recovery from employing the strategies of Wen Zhong. How can a ruler not trust the words of the virtuous and wise? The invasion of Ying succeeded through the cunning of the peddler who brought the precious brocade; the destruction of Wu arose from the honeyed words of the Chief Minister. How dare a ruler entertain the proximity of flatterers and slanderers? Yesterday dwelling on Mount Kuaiji, today dwelling in the Palace of Gusu—thus does one see the inconstancy of human affairs. Last year Yue was given to Wu; this year Wu is given to Yue—thus is the inscrutable will of Heaven revealed. Yue's lord lay upon brushwood contemplating his spleen even as he hastened to gather the rice harvest from the fields. When Wu Yuan's body floated in a leather bag upon the river, already grass grew in the courtyards below. Plans ill-conceived cannot be mended by belated regret. Yet even now, a thousand years hence, such tales strike the breast of the loyal and raise the hair of the noble. How can a man possessed of a state not be aroused by such examples?

    This is why our Majesty himself undertook to gather and perfect this work, ensuring its completeness, providing glosses and annotations for ease of reading, leaving nothing incomplete, setting down the past in upright words, concealing neither good nor evil, and presenting a clear mirror to those who come after. Profound indeed is this purpose. Yet I venture to lament one thing: Wu descended from the House of Houji; Yue traced back to the line of Yu the Great. Yet they contended like the horns of a snail, content with petty supremacy between the Huai and Si rivers, never knowing that their ancestors had once grasped the Nine Provinces, that their heirs had ruled through ages of virtue—knowing not that this came from the people, not from the land. Alas, herein lies the tragedy: Wu remained merely Wu, Yue merely Yue, neither joining the realm of China proper. How shall this not stir the lamentation of generations yet unborn?

    Then is this work merely a chronicle of Wu and Yue? Nay, it is truly a mirror and warning for all rulers and ministers throughout the ten thousand ages of the world.
  footnotes:
    - Sun Wu, one of the great military strategists; the Chinese text contains variants for his name and that of other ancient figures.
    - Wu Yuan (also written as Zi Xu) was a loyal minister of Wu who was ultimately murdered, his body placed in a leather sack and cast into the river—a historical tragedy widely celebrated in literature.
    - The image of lying on brushwood and contemplating one's spleen refers to King Goujian of Yue's suffering and determination during his period of hardship.
    - The 'Nine Provinces' (Jiuzhou) represents the traditional conception of all civilized lands under a virtuous ruler.
